Preheat your oven to 200°C, fill and boil your #kettle{}. Halve, peel and chop the @echalion shallot{1} into small pieces. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Roughly chop the @sundried tomatoes{1} and pop these in a #jug{} with the @water{450%ml}(boiling) and the @vegetable stock powder{2}, stir well and set aside.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{1} in a large ovenproof #saucepan{} over medium-high heat and add the shallot.

> If you don't have an ovenproof pan, just cook in a normal saucepan then transfer to an ovenproof dish before the risotto goes in the oven.

Stir and cook until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}. Add the garlic and @tomato puree{1} and cook for ~{1%minute} more. Stir in the @risotto rice{175%g} and cook until it is slightly translucent, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Meanwhile, pour the stock and sundried tomato mixture into the rice then add the @baby plum tomatoes{1}, bring back to the boil. Cover with a #lid{} (or some tightly fitting #foil{}).

> Transfer to an ovenproof dish, cover with a lid or foil at this point if your pan isn't ovenproof.

Pop on the top shelf of your oven and bake until the rice is cooked and the stock absorbed, ~{20-25%minutes}.

While the risotto is cooking, halve the @lemon{1/2} and squeeze the juice into a large #bowl{}. Add the @honey{1} and whisk together with a #fork{}. Trim the root from the @baby gem lettuce{1} then separate the leaves. Trim the @cucumber{1/2} then quarter lengthways. Chop widthways into small pieces.

When the risotto is cooked, remove it from your oven. Carefully take the lid off the pan and add a splash of water to loosen if you need to. Stir in a knob of @?butter{1%knob} and the @hard Italian style cheese{2}(grated). Stir together until combined. Taste and season with @?salt{} and @?pepper{} if you feel it needs it.

Add the cucumber and baby gem to your bowl of salad dressing and toss to coat. Serve the risotto in #bowls{} with the salad alongside. Enjoy!